<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="217" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1578,2037]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="216" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1578,1604]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[353,457,1578,1604]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete, with eight thoracic and about 32 abdominal chaetigers. Body length 
<quantity box="[1363,1432,1578,1605]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
, branchial crown 
<quantity box="[339,407,1614,1641]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
; maximum body width 
<quantity box="[673,758,1614,1641]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[773,878,1614,1640]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Brown colouration present especially in the thorax. Crown with five pairs of radioles each with 17 pairs of long pinnules arranged in two alternating rows along the radiole, especially in the distal half of radiole. Pinnule show a similar length (around 1/6 of the total radiolar length) and are slightly shorter in the last two distal pairs and in the first two basal pairs which appear more separated from the other pairs. Tip of radioles extremely elongated reaching 1/3 of the total radiolar length, slender but with a blunt end (
<figureCitation box="[344,446,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). Radiolar skeleton with two rows of cells. Anterior peristomial ring not visible. Posterior peristomial ring low and higher ventrally with a well separated ventral incision connected to well-developed ventral basal flanges, extending as a prominent ridge from the base of ventral-most radioles (
<figureCitation box="[1099,1234,1866,1893]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 10D, E</figureCitation>
). Peristomial eyes brown red. Dorsal lips with a rounded dorsal radiolar appendages measuring 1/4 of radiolar length. Pygidial eyes as brown clusters on lateral margins of pygidium. Thorax longer than wide. The first thoracic chaetiger bearing only two chaetae similar to the superior chaetae of the following chaetigers. From the second to the eighth thoracic chaetiger, 5 uncini in each torus. Thoracic uncini with well-developed breast, large as the distance to main fang, with approximately four rows of similar teeth above main fang, and a handle measuring approximately 1/3 of the total uncinus length, and considered as medium-short handle (0.35) (
<figureCitation box="[933,1038,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-151@15.[170,1416,453,1848]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). Companion chaetae present, with straight shaft and long mucro (
<figureCitation box="[493,594,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-151@15.[170,1416,453,1848]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
). Second to eighth thoracic chaetigers with 5 thoracic chaetae of which two superior broadly hooded chaetae (
<figureCitation box="[527,628,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
) and three inferior paleate chaetae with a mucro as long as the hood (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 10E</figureCitation>
). Abdominal uncini, in number of 4 on each torus, with 3-4 similar-sized small teeth above main fang and short handle, appearing higher than longer (
<figureCitation box="[574,674,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-151@15.[170,1416,453,1848]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
). Three broadly-hooded abdominal neurochaetae, very similar to the thoracic paleate chaetae in the first abdominal segments (
<figureCitation box="[792,892,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-151@15.[170,1416,453,1848]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 11G</figureCitation>
) and becoming narrower and more geniculate in the median abdominal segments (
<figureCitation box="[527,625,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-151@15.[170,1416,453,1848]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 11. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
). Spermathechae whitish.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636164" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4636164" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636164/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="216" startId="15.[151,250,1871,1895]" targetBox="[182,1406,461,1837]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1871,1967]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,1871,1895]" pageId="15" pageNumber="216">FIGURE 11.</emphasis>
