<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,403,150,176]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Staining pattern.</emphasis>
In both thorax and abdomen stain only ventral shields. Peristomium, thorax and abdomen intensely coloured, with larger rectangular pattern in the abdominal segments (
<figureCitation box="[1032,1135,186,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1472,1496]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,189,1442]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1448]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Amphiglena phlegreensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636160/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,312,222,248]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Variation</emphasis>
. Individuals with 8 thoracic chaetigers and up to 32 abdominal chaetigers. Mean body length of 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
and mean crown length of 
<quantity box="[501,587,258,285]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[601,685,258,284]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="29.[151,239,689,715]" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparative view of the main characters of the described Amphiglena species." pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="217" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,294,320]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Remarks</emphasis>
. Excluding 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leydig" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[443,663,294,321]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[443,468,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">A.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[509,663,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">mediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[663,667,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">,</emphasis>
this taxon is very similar to the group of species here described from the Gulf of Naples, however it has a greater number of pinnules on the radioles. The peristomial ring is more similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[181,362,366,393]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="pithecusensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[181,362,366,393]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">A. pithecusensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[370,460,366,392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[370,460,366,392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but thoracic uncini are more similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[917,1059,366,393]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="nisidensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[917,1059,366,393]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">A. nisidensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1067,1157,366,392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1067,1157,366,392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, from which it differs in having longer handles. Additionally, it has very long abdominal chaetae, similarly to 
<taxonomicName authority="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi, 2021" authorityName="Giangrande &amp; Putignano &amp; Licciano &amp; Gambi" authorityYear="2021" box="[1103,1264,403,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Amphiglena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="aenariensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1103,1264,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">A. aenariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1271,1362,402,429]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1271,1355,402,428]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="217" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,438,464]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named from 
<typeStatus box="[491,539,439,465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">type</typeStatus>
locality, since the Secca delle Fumose is within the Gulf of Pozzuoli, part of the Phlegrean Fields, a large and still active volcanic area in the Gulf of Pozzuoli (Naples). The name derives from the ancient Greek word 
<emphasis box="[379,455,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">phlego</emphasis>
=to burn.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="217" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,507,546,572]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">Distribution and Ecology.</emphasis>
The species is known only from this location (Secca delle Fumose). This site is a rocky area which is formed by rocky columnar structures (named 
<emphasis box="[911,967,582,608]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">pilae</emphasis>
) representing the columns of the ancient Roma harbour of Baia, submerged due to the tectonic subsidence of the area (bradeysism). This site is a hydrothermal vent system, where CO 
<subScript attach="left" box="[457,465,673,687]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">2</subScript>
,sulphur (H 
<subScript attach="right" box="[596,604,673,687]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">2</subScript>
S) emissions, and also hot water fluids, emerge from the bottom.A description of the area and its benthic community was provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Donnarumma, L. &amp; Appolloni, L. &amp; Chianese, E. &amp; Bruno, R. &amp; Baldrighi, E. &amp; Guglielmo, R. &amp; Russo, G. F. &amp; Zeppilli, D. &amp; Sandulli, R." box="[824,1126,690,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="217" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref18975" refString="Donnarumma, L., Appolloni, L., Chianese, E., Bruno, R., Baldrighi, E., Guglielmo, R., Russo, G. F., Zeppilli, D. &amp; Sandulli, R. (2019) Environmental and benthic community patterns of the shallow hydrothermal area of Secca delle Fumose (Baia, Naples, Italy). Frontiers in Marine Sciences, 6 (685), 1 - 15. https: // doi. org / 10.3389 / fmars. 2019.00685" type="journal article" year="2019">
Donnarumma 
<emphasis box="[985,1034,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="217">et al</emphasis>
. (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
